                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1"><span class="Apple-converted-space">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </span>Grandville Rodriquez was born on the banks of the Los Angeles River, October 25, 1941, the very day his mother, Rebecca Alonzo, age sixteen, was smuggled over the Mexican border. Coming from the rural areas of Sonora, Mexico, Rebecca was aghast at the immensity of Los Angeles while peeking through the slats of a cattle truck. She decided to name her first born Villa Grande Elias Rodriquez. Villa Grande (&ldquo;huge city&rdquo;) was later Americanized to Grandville.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">Grandville's first glimpse of Earth was of a newborn oil well, gushing oil into the sky on a stifling hot October day. Grandville's eyes rolled with the flight of the black rain as it gently fell into the Los Angeles River, forcing the slow moving animal parts from the nearby slaughterhouse to curl into black paste along the river shoreline.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">His stomach churned. It is thus understandable that he began suffering a strange intestinal disorder soon after birth, which nearly brought him to death and forced him to restrain from all foods except rotten bananas and soy milk, until the age of five. Apparently soybeans and black bananas produced enzymes that eventually were accepted by his terrorized stomach. However, soybeans and rotten bananas have their drawbacks. They lack vitamin D and C. Thus Grandville suffered from rickets and scurvy in his preschool years and spent a good spell of his young life in the bathroom.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">Grandville's mother said that despite his painful asshole and stomach, Grandville was an amazingly happy baby and rarely, if ever, cried. However, because of his early sicknesses, there were concerns in his family, which included a grandmother and a younger brother, that Grandville was retarded. Grandville attended the Bellview Retard School until the age of eight for he talked only in babbles his first seven years and never quite mastered the art of walking.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">Grandville remembers the first words he said that were understood. The event occurred at age six while he was recovering from an accident where his penis had been severed while he was playing with playpen clamps. After the operation of sewing his penis back on, a nurse in the hospital, unaware he couldn't talk, came in and asked Grandville what he wanted for breakfast. Grandville recalls he said, &ldquo;I want Rice Krispies.&rdquo;</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">It should be noted that despite his native language, Spanish, being spoken exclusively in his home, his first understandable words were in his emphasized English as he not only over-pronounced certain words but he also, at times, pronounced each syllable individually&mdash;a trait that was to stay with him all of his life. As much to the chagrin of the Chicano population of Los Angeles, Grandville never spoke in Spanish and considered Chicanos who tried to hold on to one gringo language over another as people who had lost their mind. Grandville noticed early that if you were Mexican in America, you needed to speak English or beg for an early death.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">As a child he had no friends and few inclinations, retreating into his room after school and studying the almanac. It is said at age eight when his family visited an uncle in Santa Fe, New Mexico, Grandville boldly attempted to walk, waddling up and down the aisles of the train, announcing at the top of his lungs, &ldquo;I am eight years old and I know everything there is to know. I know my name: Villa Grande Elias Rodriquez. And I know the population of every city we are passing.&rdquo; Grandville, an almanac expert, proceeded to announce the exact population of every city the train passed. Riders were shocked when they saw the population sign before the entrance to every city; Grandvllle was exactly correct.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">Despite his cockiness, Grandville did very poorly in school and after a temper tantrum in his high school physics class, combined with his .05 grade average, the school encouraged Grandville to drop out and get his GED. But he refused. He had something to teach his teacher: he did not like his physics teacher's gravity theory that had little balls romping around bigger balls with nothing whatsoever tying them together. Grandville was convinced that the motion of the larger bodies in space-time displaced space-time creating vacuum cracks and these cracks sucked smaller bodies around larger bodies, which his teacher misinterpreted as gravity. To disprove his teacher, Grandville built his science project, showcasing a giant carburetor that caused enough smog for a full day in LA, a vacuum cleaner the size of a semi and seven various size balls on engine-propelled model airplanes&mdash;all of which could only fit on the football field. The experiment resulted in an F when the biggest of these balls collided into the chest of the teacher, causing a premature death.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">Given the choice of the army or jail, Grandville was assigned the MOS of an infantry soldier and sent to guard the Korean DMZ during the postwar period. People who recall Grandville in the army say he appeared to be in a stupor most of the time and developed the habit of laughing in front of his superiors when they were loudly proclaiming their demands, the worst possible moment to laugh if you were in the military. Grandville, himself, recalls the horrors of the infantry, such as the frightening 6 a.m. jogs through the shit-filled rice paddies and the weekly bayonet assault course that required sprinting up steep mountains, which Grandville actually just waddled up, and sticking bayonets into scores of scarecrows in the muggy heat of the Korean summer. These types of activities forced Grandville into the orderly room in the wee small hours of the night and there he practiced typing, which earned him a job as company clerk, thus saving him from the horrors of being an infantry soldier.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">It is astounding to his family that despite his lack of education and suspected intelligence deficiencies, soon out of the army, Grandville married the famous Danish physicist, Janne Thousig, and moved to Copenhagen, Denmark. However, this turned out to be an unfortunate marriage as Grandville's mother-in-law considered him to be a stumbling, sloppy, belly-hanging idiot who looked like an overstuffed bird and spent more time waddling to the bathroom than to work. But Grandville did work, building elaborate electrical devices that produced painful shocks, which made it impossible for his mother-in-law to barge into the newlyweds' home unanounced. Nevertheless, these six months, before his wife decided that she loved her mother more than Grandville, proved to play an important role in Grandville's incredible impact upon world history.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">Moving back to Los Angeles, his second marriage to Francie Zweigart, a veterinarian, proved equally unfortunate. During this short marriage, Grandville developed the intense dislike of animals as his new wife's compassionate heart amassed huge quantities of animals and fleas. The animals were the worst as they not only bit, but also pissed and shitted on the furniture, forcing Grandville's rapid departure.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">But it was Grandville's third marriage that provided the most motivation for his incredible feat. This woman, a Gertrude Eddington, was a lawyer who continually prodded Grandville to become rich and insisted on having the most prestigious models of automobiles. Much to the surprise of his family, during this period, Grandville became quite successful, creating a chain of junk food grocery stores that grossed over a hundred million a year. But to his family's surprise, Grandville disappeared one day, leaving behind his third wife, their plush home and assorted luxurious automobiles, as well as his healthy, junk food grocery store chain.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">Then, suddenly after twelve years of hiding from the F.B.I., he was discovered in Canoga Park, California, with his fourth wife and her three kids from a love affair she had in her early teens.</span></p>
                        <p class="p1"><span class="s1">Grandville Rodriquez became the greatest Mexican hero of all time, first creating the underground banking system, La Raza, which offered loans with no collateral to Latinos and at zero percent interest rates. Second, he made money worthless, destroying the gringo power structure and finally, when the gringo's response was nuclear destruction of the world, he aborted their efforts. And now, Grandville, the savior of the common people of the world, has created his own museum calling it the Autobiograffiti of Grandville Rodriquez, which is a three-mile line of sign posts in the Norfolk Island Pine Forest of Kaua'i, revealing all the lies the gringo world has been telling you about him and his reasoning behind his incredible feat.</span></p>
